":"1694","1590":"1590","Kensington, Middlesex, England, United Kingdom":"Kensington, Middlesex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Bonwick, Yorkshire, England":"Bonwick, Yorkshire, England"},"en":{"1610–":"1610–Deceased","1610–Male":"1610–Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1600–1694":"1600–1694","1632–1684":"1632–1684","1587–Male":"1587–Deceased","1590–Female":"1590–Deceased","1600":"1600","1610":"1610","1632":"1632","1587":"1587","1684":"1684","1694":"1694","1590":"1590","Kensington, Middlesex, England, United Kingdom":"Kensington, Middlesex, England, United Kingdom","Bonwick, Yorkshire, England":"Bonwick, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Fox","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: nickname from a word denoting the animal (Middle English, Old English <i>fox</i>), widely used to denote a sly or cunning individual. It was also used for someone with red hair. In England this surname absorbed some early examples of surnames derived from the ancient Germanic personal names mentioned at   Faulks   and   Foulks  .","Irish: part translation of Gaelic <b>Mac an tSionnaigh</b> ‘son of the fox’ (see   Tinney  ).","Irish: also adopted for <b>Ó Catharnaigh</b>, see   Kearney  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Foxe","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Fox  .","Altered form of English   Fox  ."]},{"name":"Foxx","meanings":["Variant of   Fox  ."]},{"name":"Faulks","meanings":["English: from the Anglo-Norman French personal name <i>Fauque</i>, <i>Fauques</i>, <i>Fau(l)ques</i> (oblique case <i>Fau(l)que</i>), originally an ancient Germanic byname <i>Falco</i>, meaning ‘falcon’."]},{"name":"Foxman","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Charna, Isadore, Shmuel.","Jewish (American): variant of   Fox  ."]},{"name":"Fuchs","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Otto, Hans, Kurt, Gerhard, Fritz, Mathias, Matthias, Armin, Ulrich, Erwin, Helmut.","German and Jewish: from Middle High German <i>vuhs</i>, German <i>Fuchs</i> ‘fox’, a nickname for a sly or cunning person, or for someone with red hair. This surname is also found in France (mainly Alsace and Lorraine), Poland, Czechia, and Slovenia, often as a translation into German of corresponding Slavic nicknames or surnames. Compare   Fox   4,   Fuks  , and   Futch  ."]},{"name":"Kearney","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Seamus, Caitlin, Declan, Dermot, Donovan, Eamonn, Liam.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Catharnaigh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Catharnach</i>’, a personal name meaning ‘warlike’. Alternatively, it may be from <b>Ó Cearnaigh</b> or <b>Mac Cearnaigh</b> (from <i>cearnach</i> ‘victorious’) or from <b>Ó Ceithearnaigh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Ceithearnach</i>’, a personal name meaning ‘foot soldier’.","History: Most present-day bearers of this name are descended from Tadhg Ó Catharnaigh, killed in battle in 1084. He was nicknamed <i>An Sionnach</i> ‘the Fox’, and for this reason the Irish surname was sometimes Anglicized as   Fox  . Denis Kearney, born in Oakmont, Ireland, in 1847, was a US labor movement leader."]}]},{"name":"Bertram","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’ + <i>hramn</i> ‘raven’. Ravens were traditional symbols of wisdom in Germanic mythology; Odin was regularly accompanied by ravens called Hugin and Munin. This name was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain.  See also  Bertrand ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Douglas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname borne by one of the most powerful families in Scotland, the earls of Douglas and of Angus, also notorious in earlier times as Border reivers. In the 17th and 18th centuries it was used as a girl's name in northern England. It is now exclusively a boys' name, used throughout the English‐speaking world."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Bertram Douglas Fox was born in 1610, in Kensington, Middlesex, England, United Kingdom, his father, Henry Fox, was 23 and his mother, Emily Josephine Fox, was 21. He married Mrs Giles Fox. They were the parents of at least 2 daughters."},"et":{"1610–":"1610–Surnud","1610–Male":"1610–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1600–1694":"1600–1694","1632–1684":"1632–1684","1587–Male":"1587–Surnud","1590–Female":"1590–Surnud","1600":"1600","1610":"1610","1632":"1632","1587":"1587","1684":"1684","1694":"1694","1590":"1590","Kensington, Middlesex, England, United Kingdom":"Kensington, Middlesex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Bonwick, Yorkshire, England":"Bonwick, Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"1610–":"1610–Kuollut","1610–Male":"1610–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1600–1694":"1600–1694","1632–1684":"1632–1684","1587–Male":"1587–Kuollut","1590–Female":"1590–Kuollut","1600":"1600","1610":"1610","1632":"1632","1587":"1587","1684":"1684","1694":"1694","1590":"1590","Kensington, Middlesex, England, United Kingdom":"Kensington, Middlesex, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Bonwick, Yorkshire, England":"Bonwick, Yorkshire, England"},"fr":{"1610–":"1610–Décédé","1610–Male":"1610–Décédé","–Female":"Décédée","1600–1694":"1600–1694","1632–1684":"1632–1684","1587–Male":"1587–Décédé","1590–Female":"1590–Décédée","1600":"1600","1610":"1610","1632":"1632","1587":"1587","1684":"1684","1694":"1694","1590":"1590","Kensington, Middlesex, England, United Kingdom":"Kensington, Middlesex, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Bonwick, Yorkshire, England":"Bonwick, Everwyck, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Bertram Douglas Fox est né en 1610, à Kensington, Middlesex, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni, son père, Henry Fox, avait 23 ans et sa mère, Emily Josephine Fox, avait 21 ans. Il a épousé Mrs Giles Fox. Ils ont eu au moins 2 filles."},"de":{"1610–":"1610–Verstorben","1610–Male":"1610–Ver